<h2>Will a Redesign Hurt My Google Rankings?</h2>
<p>Done correctly, no, and often your rankings will improve. The key is a proper <strong>SEO migration</strong>:</p>
<ul>
  <li>301 redirects from old URLs to new ones</li>
  <li>Preserving and improving meta titles and descriptions</li>
  <li>Keeping your domain and main keywords in your URL structure</li>
  <li>Submitting a new sitemap to Google Search Console</li>
</ul>
<p>At Tupate Studio, every redesign includes a full SEO handover to protect your existing search traffic.</p>

<h2>How to Brief a Web Designer for a Redesign</h2>
<p>The more clearly you can articulate what you want, the better the result. Before your first meeting, prepare:</p>
<ol>
  <li><strong>3 websites you like</strong>, and what specifically you like about them</li>
  <li><strong>Your main business goal</strong>, more phone calls? More form submissions? Online sales?</li>
  <li><strong>Your target customer</strong>, who is your ideal client, and what do they need to see to trust you?</li>
  <li><strong>Your services / products</strong>, a full list, with descriptions and pricing if applicable</li>
  <li><strong>Any brand assets</strong>, logo (vector format), brand colours, fonts if you have them</li>
</ol>

<blockquote>
  "The best redesigns happen when the client and designer are aligned from the start. A clear brief saves time and money."
</blockquote>

<h2>What to Expect After the Redesign Launches</h2>
<p>A new website doesn't instantly bring traffic. Here's a realistic timeline:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Week 1–4</strong>, Google crawls and reindexes your new site. Rankings may temporarily fluctuate.</li>
  <li><strong>Month 1–3</strong>, If SEO was set up correctly, you'll start seeing improved rankings for your target keywords.</li>
  <li><strong>Month 3+</strong>, With ongoing content and link building, organic traffic grows steadily.</li>
</ul>

